Sand Creek is a dark and painful stain on our nation’s past. 
 
But we must confront our history so that future generations can learn the full story. And so we never repeat it.

Two years ago, we joined descendants, Tribal leaders, @SecDebHaaland, and other officials at the Sand Creek Massacre National Historic Site. 
 
It’s thanks to these descendants and the community members that this story has been remembered after being suppressed for so long.

It wasn’t until 2014 when I was Governor that Colorado officially apologized for the Sand Creek Massacre. 
 
I said then and it’s still our mission today that we will not run from our history and we will make sure this history continues to be told.

On November 29, 1864, hundreds of Arapaho and Cheyenne people – mostly women, children, and the elderly – were murdered at Sand Creek by U.S. Army soldiers. 
 
For the next 150 years, the horrific atrocities at Sand Creek went unacknowledged by our government.

Native American Heritage Day is an opportunity to celebrate the rich culture of our Tribal communities and honor the contributions Native Americans bring to Colorado and our nation.
 
This year it also falls on the 160th anniversary of the Sand Creek Massacre 🧵⬇️
